.subheader
  .page-label Contribute
%section.contribute-section
  %section.how-contribute
    %h2 How can I contribute ?
    %p.text-block Coding is not the only way you can contribute to Gauge. Take a look below to learn more about how you can contribute and become part of the growing gauge community.
    %p.text-block Any of the below are considered contribution and we welcome them all.

    %ul.contribution-list
      %li
        .contribution-list-item
          %h3 Test Gauge
          .icon-cl.icon-cl-1
          .desc You can report an issue you found or you can help us test Gauge and find new issues.

      %li
        .contribution-list-item
          %h3 Discuss with the Community
          .icon-cl.icon-cl-2
          .desc We have an active forum(link) where issues, features and ideas are discussed. Start a discussion, or help someone get started with Gauge. Help us build a community so Gauge can help even more people.

      %li
        .contribution-list-item
          %h3 Blog about Gauge
          .icon-cl.icon-cl-3
          .desc Maybe you’ve used Gauge is a different way, or you did an analysis of how a feature works - if you want to write about things like these, then we’d love to add them to the Gauge blog.

      %li
        .contribution-list-item
          %h3 Enhance our Examples
          .icon-cl.icon-cl-4
          .desc We’re trying to maintain a set of examples that evolve as we add new features and languages. If you’ve tried something you think would be useful to the community, please add it.
      
      %li
        .contribution-list-item
          %h3 
            Improve Documentation
          .icon-cl.icon-cl-5
          .desc If you enjoy doing a detailed analysis of how something works whether it's an API or a feature, then please help us improve our documentation. This will really help the Gauge community at large.


      %li
        .contribution-list-item
          %h3 Code for Gauge
          .icon-cl.icon-cl-6
          .desc Gauge has many repositories, all on GitHub. Gauge core is written in Golang. Gauge also has a rich plugin repository, and not everything in there is in Golang. If this is the kind of thing you like, then you can pick up any pending feature/bug, simple or complex. Just make sure you write a test and send us a pull request.

  %section.contribution-process
    %h2 Code Contribution Process
    %ul  
      %li.step1 Find an issue
      %li.step2 Assign it to Yourself
      %li.step3 Fork the Repository
      %li.step4 Talk to us about what you want to do
    %ul.block-rtl  
      %li.step8 We'll Merge your Request
      %li.step7 Fill out the CLA Form
      %li.step6 Submit a Pull Request
      %li.step5 Make your changes

  %section.help
    %h2 How Do I Get Help?
    %p.text-block
      If you're new to open source contribution then we'd suggest you pick a small bug to start with. We have issues of varying levels across all Gauge repositories, start with something simple and work your way up. We have issues tagged as
      %i Help Needed
      so this will help you pick the issues you want to start with. If you need any help getting started, then you can talk to us Gitter or email us at
    %p.text-block
      If you do send us a pull request, we’ll need you read this agreement and sign the
      %a{:href => "/cla"} Contributor License Agreement
